speaker: Programmer
text: What are the commonly used functions taking ssh_channel as a parameter?

speaker: Apiza
text: There are a lot of common functions that take ssh_channel as a parameter,

speaker: Apiza
text:
including
"void ssh_channel_free (ssh_channel channel)", 
"int channel_read_buffer (ssh_channel channel, ssh_buffer buffer, uint32_t count, int is_stderr)", 
"int ssh_channel_poll (ssh_channel channel, int is_stderr)", and
"int ssh_channel_write (ssh_channel channel, const void *data, uint32_t len)".

speaker: Programmer
text: How do I use channel_read_buffer?

speaker: Apiza
text: For example, if you have ssh_channel channel and ssh_buffer buffer, you could use\n"int nbytes = ssh_channel_read_buffer(channel, buffer, sizeof(buffer), 0);"

speaker: Programmer
text: What is the actual type of ssh_buffer?

speaker: Apiza
text: The ssh_buffer_struct consists of the following fields:\n

speaker: Apiza
text: char *data, uint32_t used, uint32_t allocated, uint32_t pos, int secure;

speaker: Programmer
text: What is the difference between ssh_channel_read_buffer and ssh_channel_read?

speaker: Apiza
text: ssh_channel_read_buffer reads data from a channel into a buffer and has parameter ssh_buffer buffer, while ssh_channel_read reads data from a channel and has parameter void *dest.

speaker: Programmer
text: How do I close a channel cleanly?

speaker: Apiza
text: int ssh_channel_close(ssh_channel channel) will close a channel.

speaker: Apiza
text: This sends an end of file and then closes the channel. You won't be able to recover any data the server was going to send or was in buffers.

speaker: Programmer
text: Is ssh_channel_send_eof necessary before ssh_channel_close?

speaker: Apiza
text: ssh_channel_send_eof is not necessary,

speaker: Apiza
text: but you should use it before ssh_channel_close if no errors have occurred.
